<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="ch-eigenvectors" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Diagonalization of Matrices</title>

<introduction>
<p>
  Learning goals:
  <ul>
    <li>
      Know how to verify if a vector is an eigenvector for a matrix.
    </li>
    <li>
      Be able to compute the eigenvectors/eigenvalues (real eigenvalues only) for a matrix using the characteristic equation.
    </li>
    <li>
      Be able to find a set of basic eigenvectors for an eigenvalue of a matrix.
    </li>
    <li>
      Given a symmetric matrix <m>A</m>, find an orthogonal matrix <m>P</m> such that <m>P^{-1}AP</m> is diagonal.
    </li>
    <li>
      Given a matrix <m>A</m>, compute the singular values of <m>A</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
      Given a matrix <m>A</m>, construct the singular value decomposition of <m>A</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
      Explain how to find the rank of a matrix from its singular value decomposition.
    </li>
    <li>
      Given a matrix <m>A</m> and its singular value decomposition, identify orthonormal bases for the four fundamental subspaces of <m>A</m>. Be familiar with the basic properties of the dot product (including the test for orthogonality).
    </li>
    <li>
      Know how to verify if a function is an inner product.
    </li>
    <li>
      Be able to compute the length of a vector and find a unit vector using an inner product.
    </li>
    <li>
      Be able to find the distance between two vectors using an inner product.
    </li>
    <li>
      Know how to check if two vectors are orthogonal given an inner product.
    </li>
  </ul>
</p>  
</introduction>

